replies.body:
I think we agree on most things, but I don't think every class should have equal access to CDR.  I strongly feel if marksmen or AD assassins want to hit 40% CDR, they should need to either bring scaling CDR runes or seriously shape their build around it, taking {{item:3158}}{{item:3078}}{{item:3142}} for example.  Likewise, AD juggernauts who really want CDR should need to build something like {{item:3158}} {{item:3065}} {{item:3071}} {{item:3800}} (or bring some mix of CDR runes).

Don't get me wrong, I don't hate those classes.  I used to main {{champion:83}}, who is an AD juggernaut.  I don't necessarily want them to be weaker by limiting their CDR itemization.  I think the items losing CDR should be given moderate compensation buffs in most cases, which would leave the classes using them balanced around the assumption that they'll not have capped CDR or will be making significant sacrifices by limiting their build in order to obtain CDR.  

The point I think we agree on is that we should need to situationally and consciously decide to focus on CDR if we want to get it.  I think we disagree on whether that should be equally true for every class and champion.  While every class can benefit from CDR if it's freely available without sacrifice, that takes away planning and cheapens the stat.  Similarly, defensive stats like health and armor are also useful on every class of champions, but they should and are more easily itemized on specific classes which those as their primary stats, ie., tanks and juggernauts who need defenses to fulfill their front-line role.

Classes which rely on their utility or CC in order to bring value feel like the most fitting CDR users because they are generally of very limited use while their abilities are on cooldown.  Classes like marksmen and skirmishers with autoattack buffs feel like the least fitting users of CDR because they can still fight while their abilities are on cooldown, so they never feel truly powerless or ability reliant.  Assassins also don't seem to fit well with CDR because they need significant cooldowns or else they become oppressive, since they should be punishable if they fail an assassination attempt, or at a minimum they should need to wait a decent window before making another attempt.  AD assassins should have their CDR more limited than AP assassins on account of all AD assassins having strong autoattacks as a fall-back plan to finish off a target while abilities are on cooldown.

In my mind, there are three primary CDR classes which should have an easier time accessing CDR: Utility supports > Supportive/true tanks > Mages.

I see Utility supports as the prime user of CDR, and they fittingly have the easiest time building the stat thanks to items like: {{item:3069}} {{item:3107}} {{item:3504}} {{item:3174}} {{item:3222}}

Utility/CC tanks can also conveniently pick up CDR items, which is fitting: {{item:2303}} {{item:3025}} {{item:3110}} {{item:3065}} {{item:3109}} {{item:3001}} {{item:3800}}
But if anything, it's getting frustrating to avoid over-capping 40% CDR as a tank, which is why I suggest removing CDR on {{item:3083}} {{item:3194}} and lowering CDR on {{item:3110}} in exchange for other buffs.

Mages actually have fairly limited CDR itemization, but I feel it's okay since they are still valued targets when their abilities are down.  They still do have 3 solid items they can build for 40% CDR: {{item:3165}} {{item:3157}} {{item:3102}} 

Like I've said before, other classes should still be able to get CDR, but it should be by meaningfully sacrificing other options, like by giving up magic resistance glyphs or by choosing {{item:3158}} or pouring gold into {{item:3078}} for examples.  One particular item that I currently dislike is {{item:3508}} because it literally seems like an item that says "hey, marksmen, want a ton of CDR tacked onto your regular crit build?"  It doesn't necessarily seem overpowered, just a poor idea for an item.  I think it should keep 10% CDR and get a different passive.
